      "It’s a good question.  I had never heard the name before buying the Arrow set.. but little did I know, I had seen two of his movies:  <strong>The Giant Spider Invasion (1975)</strong> and <strong>Blood Harvest (1987)</strong>.  The first thanks to MST3K and the second thanks to the Last Drive-In.  Then, just this past Halloween, I watched one from the set: <strong>The Demons of Ludlow (1983)</strong>.  I thought that one wasn’t too bad, but not really “good”.. just a fun little small town horror movie.  So anyway, now I know who Bill Rebane is.  He is another of these low budget horror filmmakers who was most active in and around the 70s, similar to those like Al Adamson, HG Lewis, and William Grefé.  The distinct thing about him is he is a Wisconsinite so his movies are made in a more midwestern location and style.  The documentary itself is fine, just another of those movie-by-movie account of his career, just like the Grefé one.  However, maybe it was intentional, but this one just felt a little.. off.  I think they wanted to try to give this “weird” vibe to it, so there was a lot of silence and not much “flash” to the documentary.  Still informative, but just felt a little more lifeless than the other ones.  I’ll be curious to check out the rest of his movies someday, probably in some other watchlists.. but at least I have a little context now going into them.",
