    content: [
      "Week 7.. &lt;drumroll&gt;… 80s slashers!  I don’t have high expectations for the quality of this week’s movies, but 80s slashers are the best comfort food.  Graduation Day is about as “pure” of a slasher as you can get in terms of the tropes.  Side note, I sometimes think it’d be fun to make a circular chart of slashers where most clear examples are closer to the center and the more borderline cases are towards the edge of the circle.  Like, the <strong>Nightmare on Elm Street</strong> series would flair out in the “supernatural” direction.. <strong>Dressed to Kill (1980) </strong>might be out towards a “thriller” direction.  Anyway, just a fun exercise.. either way, the point is, Graduation Day would be somewhere near the center.",
      "Even though I know slashers aren’t about the characters, I do enjoy the ones where you can get to know the characters a bit before they die, like <strong>Halloween (1978)</strong> and <strong>Friday the 13th: The Final Chapter (1984)</strong>.  This one is not like those.. I couldn’t tell you anyone’s name or any real character traits.. they are all basically just setup to be killed.  Even the final girl doesn’t have a very large role throughout most of it.  So as a slasher, it has the kills with fun special effects and the whodunit aspect, but it’s otherwise pretty forgettable.  I got what I signed up for though.",
      "6.5/10",
    ],
